                "id": "neuroscience", 
                "name": "Neuroscience"
            }
        ], 
        "researchOrganisms": [
            "C. elegans", 
            "Mouse"
        ], 
        "abstract": {
            "content": [
                {
                    "type": "paragraph", 
                    "text": "Axon injury triggers dramatic changes in gene expression. While transcriptional regulation of injury-induced gene expression is widely studied, less is known about the roles of RNA binding proteins (RBPs) in post-transcriptional regulation during axon regeneration. In <i>C. elegans</i> the CELF (CUGBP and Etr-3 Like Factor) family RBP UNC-75 is required for axon regeneration. Using crosslinking immunoprecipitation coupled with deep sequencing (CLIP-seq) we identify a set of genes involved in synaptic transmission as mRNA targets of UNC-75. In particular, we show that UNC-75 regulates alternative splicing of two mRNA isoforms of the SNARE Syntaxin/<i>unc-64</i>. In <i>C. elegans</i> mutants lacking <i>unc-75</i> or its targets, regenerating axons form growth cones, yet are deficient in extension. Extending these findings to mammalian axon regeneration, we show that mouse <i>Celf2</i> expression is upregulated after peripheral nerve injury and that <i>Celf2</i> mutant mice are defective in axon regeneration. Further, mRNAs for several Syntaxins show CELF2 dependent regulation. Our data delineate a post-transcriptional regulatory pathway with a conserved role in regenerative axon extension."
                }
            ]
        }
